t262.text: It’s now time for me to move away from The Twitters - please assist Terrance and I in our quest to complete #30DaysOfCycling in April by letting us know what our route will be called. Thanks for playing!

t263.text: The modified Fluffy route should be called...

t264.text: Instead of going North on Royal Parade and making Fluffy’s head, we will return in the Easterly direction marked in orange(ish). Now comes the big question and it’s important.

t265.text: That route has way too many interactions with motorised vehicles for me to be comfortable rolling with Terrance at the moment. The route we will be taken is marked below with the change being marked in orange(ish).pic.twitter.com/Xo3T9AZ17L

t266.text: A favoured route of @TerranceTownie (and @RangaRob2 and @SkepticReview89) #FluffyTheSeahorse. Fluffy looks like this:pic.twitter.com/POlw2ziV5l

t267.text: These ten metres will need to be crossed twice and the rest of the route is pedestrians/cyclists only. We will be rolling slowly—as per our usual pace—for an approximately five kilometre round-trip. And now the important bits of this wee rant: what to call the route, of course!

t268.text: Such that we feel safe and confident in our rolls together afte not rolling together for such a long period of time, we will be staying close to home on a route that only requires interacting with motorised vehicle for a stretch of road approximately ten metres.

t269.text: Yes, that’s correct: on Wednesday, 1 Apr 2020, Terrance and I will be having our first roll together after 43 days of not rolling together. This will be the first day of #30DaysOfCycling and our aim is to do all thirty.

t270.text: I’ll also be doing my two fifteen minute spins on Philip, the exercise bicycle. Philip arrived last Friday and we’ve spent approximately 30 minutes together every day since then. I’m doing Philip at the moment such that I will be ready to mount @TerranceTownie next Wednesday.

t271.text: The chat with my workplace is not the only activity scheduled for today as I will be going for my daily constitutional and drop postcards into the. letter box so they can start making their way to various ports around the world.

t5375.text: Wash your hands and don’t touch your face. And keep it up. Take care of yourselves and each other. Be kind to each other. We’ll get through this. Together.

t5376.text: Support local businesses - they desperately need it - but do it via takeaway or delivery. If you’re forced to leave your home because you work in an essential service, or you need to buy essentials, then please ensure that you’re keeping safe distance from others.

t5377.text: So please stay home. This is an extraordinary and unnatural request, but it’s necessary. Stay home. Don’t go out looking for exemptions. Don’t think this doesn’t apply to you. Don’t think it’s hysterical or disproportionate.

t5378.text: Unlike nuclear fallout, we do have real control over what is to come. What happens will depend on the choices that we all make – politicians and citizens alike. This is an unprecedented health crisis. It affects all of us, and we can only get through it by working together.

t5379.text: Now we aren’t confronting the end of the world – but we are facing the next most serious thing. In the coming days and weeks, the lives and livelihoods of hundreds of thousands of Australians will be in the balance. It’s the most serious challenge we’ve faced as a society.

t5380.text: In Australia, we’ve been lucky enough to be a few weeks behind the infection curve of Europe and the United States. What we’ve been left with is that “On the Beach” sense of dread – the dread of waiting for a catastrophe that we can see unfolding overseas.pic.twitter.com/uavbrqYtEG
